elements.content: Six novel coordination polymers, {[M2(L1)2(μ2-L1)2(4,4′-bipy)2]·CH3OH} n (HL1 = 3-(4-carboxylphenylamino)-1-ferrocenyl-2-butylen-1-one, 4,4′-bipy = 4,4′-bipyridine) (M = Zn (1) or Cd (2)), {[Cd2(η2-L2)2(μ2-η2-L2)2(4,4′-bipy)2]·CH3OH} n (HL2 = N-phenylanthranilic acid) (3), {[Cd2(μ-L3)(μ2-L3)(η2-L3)(4,4′-bipy)2(H2O)2]·NO3} n (HL3 = cinnamic acid) (4), {[Cd2(μ2-L4)4(4,4′-bipy)2]·2H2O} n (HL4 = hippuric acid) (5), and {[Cd2(μ2-η2-L5-η2)2(SO4)(4,4′-bipy)2(H2O)2]·5H2O} n (HL5 = 1-(carboxymethyl)-1,3-benzimidazol-3-ium-3-acetate) (6), have been synthesized and structurally characterized by single-crystal X-ray diffraction method. Polymers 1−4 exhibit one-dimensional (1-D) ladder-like structures, in which carboxylate ligands bridge two metal ions forming dinuclear cores, and 4,4′-bipy ligands link these cores. In polymers 5 and 6, the carboxylate-linked chains [Cd2(μ2-L4)4] n or mixed carboxylate and SO4 2− linked [Cd2(μ2-η2-L5-η2)2(SO4)] n chains are bridged by 4,4′-bipy ligands to form two-dimensional (2-D) sheet structures. In addition, the solution-state differential pulse voltammetries of polymers 1 and 2 were determined, and the photoluminescence properties of polymers 3−6 were investigated. The thermal properties of polymers 1−6 were determined as well.

elements.clean_text:
Introduction

Investigations show that the designed construction of metal-organic polymers is influenced by many factors such as the nature of the organic building block, the coordination preference of the central metal ion, crystallization conditions, the metal/ligand ratio and preparation methods, etc. Consequently, people found that the geometry of ligating atoms within a polynucleating ligand, the flexibility of the ligand backbone, and the additional functional groups of the ligands all play important roles in directing the extended structure of the resulting complex. Thus, considerable efforts have been devoted to choose or design various ligands to construct novel coordination frameworks with tunable properties.

elements.content: In this context, two kinds of ligands have attracted much interest in the coordination chemistry field. The first is carboxylate compound, which can adopt a variety of bonding modes to metals, including (i) terminal monodentate, (ii) chelating to a single metal, (iii) bridging bidentate to two metals in a syn-syn-, syn-anti-, or anti-anti- fashion, and (iv) bridging tridentate to two metal centers. Thus, one-, two- or three-dimensional infinite frameworks can be generated. The second is rigid 4,4′-bipyridine (4,4′-bipy), which has been employed as a rod-type two-connector in numerous studies to construct a large number of topologies, including chains, diamond-like, honeycomb, square-grid, ladder or brick-wall structures, and so on.

elements.content: However, the reported coordination polymers with both carboxylate and 4,4′-bipy ligands are still limited (4,4′-bipy-based coordination polymers with different carboxylato ligands are listed in Table ), and the investigation of carboxylato ligands with bulky substituents is comparatively rare. We believe that the carboxylate compounds containing a bulky group may feature interesting coordination abilities in the presence of organic N-containing ligands. So we designed and choose the carboxylate ligands 3-(4-carboxylphenylamino)-1-ferrocenyl-2-butylen-1-one (HL1), N-phenylanthranilic acid (HL2), cinnamic acid (HL3), hippuric acid (HL4), and 1-(carboxymethyl)-1,3-benzimidazol-3-ium-3-acetate (HL5) (Scheme ) to react with metal ions. It is to be noted that we also choose 4,4′-bipy as a secondary metal linker in the synthesis process. In particular, the synthesis of HL1 and partial characterization of the polymer 1 were reported by us in a preliminary communication. In this paper six novel coordination polymers, {[M2(L1)2(μ2-L1)2(4,4′-bipy)2]·MeOH} n (M = Zn (1) or Cd (2)), {[Cd2(η2-L2)2(μ2-η2-L2)2(4,4′-bipy)2]·MeOH} n (3), {[Cd2(μ-L3)(μ2-L3)(η2-L3)(4,4′-bipy)2(H2O)2]·NO3} n (4), {[Cd2(μ2-L4)4(4,4′-bipy)2]·2H2O} n (5), and {[Cd2(μ2-η2-L5-η2)2(SO4)(4,4′-bipy)2(H2O)2]·5H2O} n (6), are reported. The polymers 1−4 exhibit 1-D ladder-like structures, and polymers 5 and 6 possess 2-D network structures. Their thermal, fluorescent, and electrochemical properties were investigated.

Experimental Section

General Details

All chemicals were of reagent grade quality obtained from commercial sources and were used without further purification. Ligands 3-(4-carboxylphenylamino)-1-ferrocenyl-2-butylen-1-one (HL1) and 1-(carboxymethyl)-1,3-benzimidazol-3-ium-3-acetate (HL5) were prepared according to literature methods. Their sodium salt was prepared by their reaction with sodium methoxide.

elements.content: C, H, N, and S microanalyses were carried out on a FLASH EA 1112 analyzer. IR data were recorded on a BRUKER TENSOR 27 spectrophotometer with KBr pellets in the 400−4000 cm−1 region. TG-DSC measurements were performed by heating the sample from 20 to 800 °C at a rate of 10 °C·min−1 in air on a Netzsch STA 409PC differential thermal analyzer. Differential pulse voltammetry studies of complexes 1 and 2 were recorded with an CHI650 electrochemical analyzer utilizing the three-electrode configuration of a Pt working electrode, a Pt auxiliary electrode, and a commercially available saturated calomel electrode as the reference electrode with a pure N2 gas inlet and outlet. The measurements were performed in DMF solution containing tetraethyl ammonium perchlorate (n-Bu4NClO4) (0.1 mol·dm−3) as supporting electrolyte, which has a 50 ms pulse width and a 20 ms sample width. The potential was scanned from +0.2 to +1.0 V at scan rate of 20 mV s−1. Fluorescence spectra of complexes 3−6 were characterized at room temperature by a F-4500 fluorescence spectrophotometer (240 nm/min).

elements.content: It is to be pointed out that the utilization of 4,4′-bipy ligands benefits the construction of novel ladder-like polymers containing dimeric cores built by bulky carboxylates. When the carboxylate ligands with bulky groups (ferrocenyl or phenyl groups), HL1, NaL2, NaL3, NaL4, and NaL5, react with metal ions, the bulky ferrocenyl or phenyl groups hold the oxygen atoms of carboxylate groups to coordinate to more metal ions simultaneously. However the ligand L4 coordinates more than two Cd(II) ions. This is may be due to reduction of the steric effect of the phenyl group by the relatively long chain -C(O)-NH-CH2- between the phenyl and carboxylate groups. When the dimeric cores were produced, the 4,4′-bipy ligands can bridge these sub-building blocks to form 1-D or 2-D frameworks.

This anti-syn bonding mode of carboxylate of the L1− leads to a chair conformation of this eight-membered metallacycle. The Zn···Zn intradimer distance of 1 is significantly longer that of the reported complexes with dimeric cores, [Zn2(μ-OOCFc)4(3-PyCOOCH3)2] (Fc = (η5-C5H5)Fe(η5-C5H4)) (Zn···Zn = 2.934(11) Å) and {[Zn2(μ2-OOCCH(CH3)CFc)4(bpa)]·2MeOH} n (bpa = 1,2-bis(4-pyridyl)ethane) (Zn···Zn = 2.928(9) Å) and close to that of the dimer [(η1-cyclo-C4H8C2H4C5Me4)Zn(μ-OAc)]2 (Zn···Zn = 3.821 Å). Obviously, the difference of the intradimer Zn···Zn distance is due to the difference of coordination mode of the carboxylate. In compounds [Zn2(μ-OOCFc)4(3-PyCOOCH3)2] or {[Zn2(μ2-OOCCH(CH3)CFc)4(bpa)]·2MeOH} n , the four FcCOO− or four FcC(CH3)CHCOO− all exhibit syn−syn bridging geometry. The formation of the dimeric core in dimer [(η1-cyclo-C4H8C2H4C5Me4)Zn(μ-OAc)]2 is similar to that in polymer 1.

elements.content: Compared the structures of polymers 1−4 with that of polymer 5, we found that the steric effects of carboxylate substituent may affect the structures of the resulting carboxylate-based building blocks. When these carboxylate ligands, L1, L2, L3, and L4 reacted with metal ions, two kinds of structures, dimeric [Zn2(μ2-L1)2]2+, [Cd2(μ2-L1)2]2+, [Cd2(μ2-η2-L2)2]2+, and [Cd2(μ-L3)(μ2-L3)]2+ cores or polymeric [Cd(μ2-L4)2] n chain, were formed. Obviously, the bulky phenyl groups hold the oxygen atoms of neighboring carboxylate groups of L1, L2, and L3 to coordinate to more metal ions. However, the long chain -C(O)-NH-CH2- between the phenyl and carboxylate groups of L4 reduces the steric effect of phenyl group, and thus L4 can bridge more Cd(II) ions to lead to carboxylate-based chains. The similar case can be found in the reported Pb-carboxylate compounds.

Fluorescence Spectra of Crystalline Polymers 3-6 

Metal-organic polymers have been reported to have the ability to affect the emission wavelength and intensity of the organic material through metal coordination. Usually metal-organic coordination polymers with the cadmium ion exhibit photoluminescent properties. The fluorescence properties of complexes 3-6 and the corresponding ligands NaL2, NaL3, NaL4, and NaL5 were examined in the solid state at room temperature.

elements.content: As shown in Figure a, the emission of NaL2 and complex 3 were observed in the range of 290−315 nm by selective excitation at 280 nm. The free NaL2 ligand shows a sharp peak with a maximum emission at 304 nm, whereas complex 3 shows a weak broad emission band around 315 nm. It can be seen from Figure b that the polymer 4 and ligand NaL3 have similar emission spectrum under the same excitation wavelength effect at 330 nm. The fluorescence of free ligand NaL3 is very weak, and complex 4 shows a sharp peak with a maximum emission at 354 nm. The maximum fluorescence bands all are basically unchanged, whereas the fluorescence intensity of complex 4 is visible enhanced, which may be attributed to ligand-to-metal charge transfer (LMCT) fluorescent emission since the ligand decreases the energy when coordinated to the metal centers. Up to complex 5 and ligand NaL4, they show similar emission spectra under the same excitation wavelength at 280 nm (Figure c). The maximum emission of polymer 5 and ligand NaL4 are at 315 and 312 nm, respectively. The fluorescence intensity of complex 5 is visible weakened. Obviously, the fluorescence emission of the complex might be attributed to ligand-to-ligand charge transfer (L* → L). The fluorescence spectra of the ligand NaL5 and the corresponding complex 6 are depicted in Figure d. Excitation at 280 nm leads to intense fluorescence signals at approximately 344 nm for free NaL5 ligand and 354 nm for complex 6, respectively. Compared with the emission spectrum of NaL5, a red shift of 10 nm in 6 has been observed. The emissions of complex 6 may be assigned to the ligand-to-ligand charge transfer.

Conclusion

A series of novel metal-organic supramolecular architectures with bulky carboxylate and rigid 4,4-bipy ligands have been prepared and structurally characterized. The elemental analyses, IR data, and thermal data are consistent with the X-ray analysis results. Complexes 1-4 exhibit a 1-D ladder-like structure. Polymers 5 and 6 show interesting 2-D layer built up by ladder-like SBUs. It is worth emphasizing that the self-assembly reaction of metal ions with ferrocenyl carboxylate in the dark is an effective route for preparation of novel coordination polymer containing ferrocene group.

One very strong exothermic peak at 476 °C can be observed on the DSC curve of polymer 3, it first loses the methanol molecule in the temperature range of 104.3−284.4 °C (observed 2.18%, calculated 2.09%). Second polymer 3 loses weight from 284.4 to 439.5 °C (observed 63.1%) and then loses weight from 439.5 to 524.4 °C (observed 16.94%). The total lost weight corresponds to the decomposition of the L2 and 4,4′-bipy ligands (observed 80.04%, calculated 80.2%). Finally, a plateau region is observed from 524.4 to 800 °C. The final white residue is 2CdO (observed 17.78%, calculated 17.71%).

The polymer 4 indicates three steps of weight lost. It first loses the two coordinated water molecules in the temperature range of 99.6−303.4 °C (observed 3.8%, calculated 3.34%); second, it loses weight from 303.4 to 445.6 °C (observed 65.1%); and third, it loses weight from 445.6 to 552.7 °C (observed 7.3%). The latter two steps of weight lost corresponds to the decomposition of the L3, NO3 − anion, and 4,4′-bipy ligands. Finally, a plateau region is observed from 552.7 to 700 °C. The final white residue is 2CdO (observed 23.80%, calculated 23.85%). There are two small endothermic peaks at 130.4 and 249.6 °C, and one very strong exothermic peak at 364.1 °C on the DSC curve of polymer 4.

One weak endothermic peak (279 °C), one strong exothermic peak (447 °C), and one weak exothermic peak (512 °C) can be observed on the DSC curve of polymer 5. It first loses the crystallized water molecules in the temperature range of 129−264 °C (observed 2.44%, calculated 2.72%) and then loses weight from 332 to 524 °C (observed 78.61%). Finally, a plateau region is observed from 524 to 800 °C. A white amorphous residue of 2CdO (observed 19.13%, calculated 19.42%) remained.

TGA data exhibits that polymer 6 is stable up to 99 °C, loses weight from 99 to 276 °C (observed 15.58%, calculated 16.66%) corresponding to losses of coordinated and crystallized water molecules, and goes on losing weight from 276 to 567 °C (observed 59.01%) assigned to decomposition of the organic units of L5 anions and 4,4′-bipy, and then shows a plateau region from 567 to 740 °C. A white amorphous residue of 2CdO remained (observed 25.41%, calculated 25.27%). One weak endothermic peak (130 °C) and one weak exothermic peak (538 °C) on the DSC curve of 6 can be observed.

In conclusion, the thermal data of polymers 1−6 are in reasonable agreement with the crystal structure analysis.

The weight-average molecular weights (M w) are 3.327 × 104 and 2.653 × 104, for polymers 1 and 2, respectively. Thus, we can confirm that polymers 1 and 2 show some stability in DMF solution.
